00:12:46.560 --> 00:12:49.390
ledgers recording
property rights.

00:12:49.390 --> 00:12:51.090
So you can have
one bank recording

00:12:51.090 --> 00:12:53.560
the property rights, another
bank recording a property

00:12:53.560 --> 00:12:54.060
right.

00:12:54.060 --> 00:12:56.370
It could be the
ownership of equities.

00:12:56.370 --> 00:12:59.370
It could be cash
called payments.

00:12:59.370 --> 00:13:02.220
So there's a lot of direct
costs that it can lower.

00:13:02.220 --> 00:13:05.460
And I would say in the
permissioned blockchain space,

00:13:05.460 --> 00:13:09.540
a lot of big banks are looking
at that very first point.

00:13:09.540 --> 00:13:14.100
We just lower our direct
costs of the back office.

00:13:14.100 --> 00:13:16.540
Stop there, straight and simple.

00:13:16.540 --> 00:13:19.520
We have a lot less
reconciliation costs.

00:13:19.520 --> 00:13:22.700
Privacy and data leakage costs.

00:13:22.700 --> 00:13:25.820
I call it both privacy,
which sounds like Hugo

00:13:25.820 --> 00:13:28.730
and I want my personal
privacy, or I just

00:13:28.730 --> 00:13:31.640
know Facebook is taking my data.

00:13:31.640 --> 00:13:33.380
I call that data leakage.

00:13:33.380 --> 00:13:36.600
I'm not terribly
worried about it.

00:13:36.600 --> 00:13:37.790
But it's something.

00:13:37.790 --> 00:13:38.730
Alene.

00:13:38.730 --> 00:13:41.120
AUDIENCE: So I'm very curious,
is there a use case here?

00:13:41.120 --> 00:13:43.190
Because I really
fail to see one.

00:13:43.190 --> 00:13:46.520
I could see privacy in the sense
that you could transfer coins

00:13:46.520 --> 00:13:48.872
from anonymous spenders
to anonymous receivers

00:13:48.872 --> 00:13:50.330
and you could even
hide the amount.

00:13:50.330 --> 00:13:53.018
And that's useful for
business, because businesses

00:13:53.018 --> 00:13:55.310
don't want other businesses
knowing what they're up to.

00:13:55.310 --> 00:13:56.743
But what other
use case is there?

00:13:56.743 --> 00:13:58.910
GARY GENSLER: Oh, I think
it's a very good question.

00:13:58.910 --> 00:14:00.285
Anybody have an
answer for Alene?

00:14:00.285 --> 00:14:02.120
Because I do, but
I just-- do others?

00:14:02.120 --> 00:14:06.150
Like a business
use case where you

00:14:06.150 --> 00:14:10.710
might have users not
giving up as much

00:14:10.710 --> 00:14:14.320
of their data and privacy.

00:14:14.320 --> 00:14:15.930
I'm going to use Uber.

00:14:15.930 --> 00:14:18.060
Oh, did you--

00:14:18.060 --> 00:14:20.880
AUDIENCE: Yeah, I think
an example I can think of

00:14:20.880 --> 00:14:23.482
is, for example,
the hedge fund in--

00:14:23.482 --> 00:14:24.690
GARY GENSLER: The which fund?

00:14:24.690 --> 00:14:25.410
AUDIENCE: Hedge fund.

00:14:25.410 --> 00:14:25.810
GARY GENSLER: Hedge fund.

00:14:25.810 --> 00:14:27.750
AUDIENCE: In asset
management, you

00:14:27.750 --> 00:14:31.230
don't want to know, because for
example, also the hedge fund,

00:14:31.230 --> 00:14:33.570
they hide behind the brokers.

00:14:33.570 --> 00:14:36.900
They have certain
swaps with the brokers

00:14:36.900 --> 00:14:40.620
so they don't have to review
the acquisition they viewed.

00:14:40.620 --> 00:14:44.280
And also they try to do their
position under the 5 percentage

00:14:44.280 --> 00:14:45.460
threshold.

00:14:45.460 --> 00:14:48.600
So in this way,
because any action--

00:14:48.600 --> 00:14:51.850
their action maybe can move
the market over a certain stop.

00:14:51.850 --> 00:14:54.450
GARY GENSLER: OK, so there
is a commercial situation

00:14:54.450 --> 00:14:55.500
as an asset manager.

00:14:55.500 --> 00:14:57.270
I might not want
others to know what

00:14:57.270 --> 00:14:59.743
trades I'm doing, what
positions I'm taking.

00:14:59.743 --> 00:15:01.410
I was going to use a
personal situation.

00:15:01.410 --> 00:15:05.400
You could envision Uber having
been created on a blockchain.

00:15:05.400 --> 00:15:06.680
It's not on a blockchain.

00:15:06.680 --> 00:15:09.660
But I'm saying you could
have envisioned it--

00:15:09.660 --> 00:15:16.690
riders, equipment owners
called car owners, and drivers.

00:15:16.690 --> 00:15:19.450
It's like three communities--
who owns the car,

00:15:19.450 --> 00:15:22.180
who drives the car,
who needs the cars--

00:15:22.180 --> 00:15:24.790
coming together in a blockchain.

00:15:24.790 --> 00:15:28.510
And maybe part of the reason I'm
comfortable with a blockchain

00:15:28.510 --> 00:15:29.110
Uber--

00:15:29.110 --> 00:15:32.680
maybe, maybe-- is I might
have a few girlfriends.

00:15:32.680 --> 00:15:34.330
And I don't want
anybody tracking

00:15:34.330 --> 00:15:36.010
that I'm visiting
different girlfriends.

00:15:36.010 --> 00:15:39.772
This would be-- you would call
it privacy, but perfectly--

00:15:39.772 --> 00:15:40.800
I'm single.

00:15:40.800 --> 00:15:41.840
I'm single.

00:15:41.840 --> 00:15:46.780
But I'm just saying that it's
a perfectly legitimate thing.

00:15:46.780 --> 00:15:48.790
Do I want to share that data?

00:15:48.790 --> 00:15:50.810
We all share a
tremendous amount of data

00:15:50.810 --> 00:15:54.550
if we use a credit card that--

00:15:54.550 --> 00:15:58.330
particularly in today's world
of machine learning and AI,

00:15:58.330 --> 00:16:00.850
that you can take
somebody's spending patterns

00:16:00.850 --> 00:16:03.070
and really narrow it down.

00:16:03.070 --> 00:16:05.560
Let's, for instance,
say that I have

00:16:05.560 --> 00:16:10.660
a certain religious affiliation
or a certain pro-guns

00:16:10.660 --> 00:16:15.280
or anti-guns or any
orientation I might have.

00:16:15.280 --> 00:16:17.440
You get enough
spending patterns,

00:16:17.440 --> 00:16:21.710
you can sort of piece
together that's probably you.

00:16:21.710 --> 00:16:23.163
That's probably your religion.

00:16:23.163 --> 00:16:24.830
That's probably your
sexual orientation.

00:16:24.830 --> 00:16:26.497
That's probably the
country you're from,

00:16:26.497 --> 00:16:30.440
the ethnic group if you pull
enough spending pattern coupled

00:16:30.440 --> 00:16:33.050
with machine learning and AI.

00:16:33.050 --> 00:16:36.830
So use case is people are really
talking about, well, maybe

00:16:36.830 --> 00:16:38.240
there's something
that I can give

00:16:38.240 --> 00:16:41.300
a little privacy-preserving
attribute.

00:16:41.300 --> 00:16:44.240
It won't be the dominant
use case, but something.

00:16:44.240 --> 00:16:48.130
And this class today is
just about economics.

00:16:48.130 --> 00:16:52.355
That's a legitimate economic
thing that's going on here.

00:16:52.355 --> 00:16:53.480
Was there a hand over here?

00:16:56.210 --> 00:16:58.100
Censorship risk.

00:16:58.100 --> 00:17:00.020
Basically that-- oh, I'm sorry.

00:17:00.020 --> 00:17:01.710
AUDIENCE: Can I ask
a related question?

00:17:01.710 --> 00:17:04.369
So in terms of the
privacy, there is--

00:17:04.369 --> 00:17:08.550
[INAUDIBLE] mentioned those
financial institutions,

00:17:08.550 --> 00:17:12.780
like before this, they can just
keep their data inside and only

00:17:12.780 --> 00:17:15.099
maybe reveal that to regulators.

00:17:15.099 --> 00:17:16.849
But if we use the
blockchain, they

00:17:16.849 --> 00:17:19.329
need to make all those
transactions public.

00:17:19.329 --> 00:17:21.319
And it's kind of
like the other--

00:17:21.319 --> 00:17:23.554
it's like the opposite
to keeping it private.

00:17:26.210 --> 00:17:28.860
GARY GENSLER: So to the
regulators you said?

00:17:28.860 --> 00:17:31.850
AUDIENCE: Like, say one
thing it keeps you anonymous.

00:17:31.850 --> 00:17:34.130
So that's kind of
protection of privacy.

00:17:34.130 --> 00:17:36.020
On the other side, we
need to make public

00:17:36.020 --> 00:17:41.030
all the information, which
may otherwise just involve

00:17:41.030 --> 00:17:43.017
some certain institutions.

00:17:43.017 --> 00:17:43.850
GARY GENSLER: Right.

00:17:43.850 --> 00:17:45.728
So you're abso-- remind
me your first name.

00:17:45.728 --> 00:17:46.520
AUDIENCE: Jennifer.

00:17:46.520 --> 00:17:47.478
GARY GENSLER: Jennifer.

00:17:47.478 --> 00:17:48.350
Jennifer is right.

00:17:48.350 --> 00:17:49.890
There is a tension--

00:17:49.890 --> 00:17:53.840
the traditional blockchains
like Bitcoin have both.

00:17:53.840 --> 00:17:56.000
They have-- they
mask a lot of data

00:17:56.000 --> 00:17:58.040
because of the pseudoanonymity.

00:17:58.040 --> 00:18:00.020
But it's not truly
completely masked,

00:18:00.020 --> 00:18:03.290
because you can use
forensics and track things.

00:18:03.290 --> 00:18:08.700
And to verify a permission list
blockchain, it's all public.

00:18:08.700 --> 00:18:09.690
So I agree with you.

00:18:09.690 --> 00:18:10.995
It sort of goes both ways.

00:18:14.260 --> 00:18:16.930
There are technical ways,
whether through zero knowledge

00:18:16.930 --> 00:18:20.280
proofs and other ways,
to have more privacy.

00:18:20.280 --> 00:18:24.360
But I'm saying there's a
legitimate economic cause.

00:18:24.360 --> 00:18:26.940
Paul Krugman's the last
sentence in his op-ed

00:18:26.940 --> 00:18:28.440
was "tell me a use case."

00:18:28.440 --> 00:18:30.990
Tell me-- remember Krugman's--

00:18:30.990 --> 00:18:32.130
he's a Nobel laureate.

00:18:32.130 --> 00:18:33.210
Paul is brilliant.

00:18:33.210 --> 00:18:36.250
And he writes eloquently
for the New York Times.

00:18:36.250 --> 00:18:39.220
But there are-- and
Jennifer, you're right.

00:18:39.220 --> 00:18:40.560
It's not perfect yet.

00:18:40.560 --> 00:18:46.540
But there are privacy attributes
that you can give to a system.

00:18:46.540 --> 00:18:49.060
I do want to clarify, I
only have one girlfriend.

00:18:49.060 --> 00:18:51.180
She lives in New York.

00:18:51.180 --> 00:18:52.780
I just want to make sure.

00:18:52.780 --> 00:18:56.500
It was a hypothetical
about Uber.

00:18:56.500 --> 00:18:57.740
Realized we're on film.

00:18:57.740 --> 00:18:59.740
ROB GENSLER: Now they'll
just all think it's me.

00:18:59.740 --> 00:19:02.765
[LAUGHTER]

00:19:02.765 --> 00:19:03.890
GARY GENSLER: There you go.

00:19:03.890 --> 00:19:04.432
There you go.

00:19:08.320 --> 00:19:08.950
Thank you, Rob.

00:19:11.740 --> 00:19:12.880
There was a story--

00:19:12.880 --> 00:19:13.380
no.

00:19:13.380 --> 00:19:16.490
OK, settlement.

00:19:16.490 --> 00:19:17.900
We've talked about this.

00:19:17.900 --> 00:19:21.550
I think if you don't have some
economics around settlement,

00:19:21.550 --> 00:19:25.030
that you don't need
some immutable record

00:19:25.030 --> 00:19:29.290
of the movement of a right,
particularly a property right,

00:19:29.290 --> 00:19:33.400
you might just as well just stay
with a traditional database.

00:19:33.400 --> 00:19:36.530
I'm not sure I'm entirely
right about that.

00:19:36.530 --> 00:19:40.750
There might be some permissioned
blockchain worthwhile.

00:19:40.750 --> 00:19:42.610
But I'm kind of a
view if you're not

00:19:42.610 --> 00:19:46.030
moving something that matters--

00:19:46.030 --> 00:19:49.000
and settlement means
something that's final.

00:19:49.000 --> 00:19:52.450
We talked briefly six
or eight lectures ago

00:19:52.450 --> 00:19:57.910
about that old lawsuit in
Scotland, the Crawford case,

00:19:57.910 --> 00:20:02.270
that if James steals $1
from me but then hands

00:20:02.270 --> 00:20:05.360
the dollar to Andrew, I can't
get it back from Andrew.

00:20:05.360 --> 00:20:07.790
I have no legal rights to
get my dollar from Andrew.

00:20:07.790 --> 00:20:10.250
I might have legal
rights about James.

00:20:10.250 --> 00:20:11.430
But it's final.

00:20:11.430 --> 00:20:13.940
There's final settlement.

00:20:13.940 --> 00:20:16.500
It's Andrew's dollar.

00:20:16.500 --> 00:20:20.370
So there's some things that
you just want finality.

00:20:20.370 --> 00:20:24.240
One thing I would talk about
is a lot of merchants in the US

00:20:24.240 --> 00:20:30.390
don't like paying 2 and 1/2
to 3% of all their sales

00:20:30.390 --> 00:20:31.910
to the payment system--

00:20:31.910 --> 00:20:33.690
Visa, First Data, and so forth.

00:20:33.690 --> 00:20:37.470
A lot of that goes to the banks,
not to Visa and First Data.

00:20:37.470 --> 00:20:41.400
And a lot of that is also for
what's called chargebacks.

00:20:41.400 --> 00:20:42.990
So I was the chief
financial officer

00:20:42.990 --> 00:20:45.180
of the Hillary campaign.

00:20:45.180 --> 00:20:49.140
Now, it was really lousy that
we lost for a lot of reasons

00:20:49.140 --> 00:20:52.730
beyond this discussion
about blockchain.

00:20:52.730 --> 00:20:55.670
But I continued to be the
CFO for the next six months,

00:20:55.670 --> 00:20:58.250
because we had to
wind down a campaign.

00:20:58.250 --> 00:21:01.190
And we had to deal with
what I called the computer

00:21:01.190 --> 00:21:03.800
and refrigerator graveyard.

00:21:03.800 --> 00:21:07.160
The hundreds of people we
had working at headquarters

00:21:07.160 --> 00:21:08.120
left the equipment.

00:21:08.120 --> 00:21:10.920
And they left.

00:21:10.920 --> 00:21:13.220
But the other thing I had
to deal with for 60 days

00:21:13.220 --> 00:21:14.270
was chargebacks.

00:21:14.270 --> 00:21:17.990
Did you know that
donors could go to Visa

00:21:17.990 --> 00:21:22.960
and say, no, I didn't
really buy that donation,

00:21:22.960 --> 00:21:24.500
whether it was $50--

00:21:24.500 --> 00:21:28.960
low dollar-- or $2,700.

00:21:28.960 --> 00:21:36.370
And so I have a personal sense
of this whole chargeback thing.

00:21:36.370 --> 00:21:38.260
Now, donations to a
political campaign

00:21:38.260 --> 00:21:41.090
are different than
services you buy.

00:21:41.090 --> 00:21:43.030
But it's something
merchants deal with a lot.

00:21:43.030 --> 00:21:43.460
Hugo.

00:21:43.460 --> 00:21:45.127
AUDIENCE: Are merchants
responsible then

00:21:45.127 --> 00:21:47.680
to pay Visa to
refund the client?

00:21:47.680 --> 00:21:50.593
Or is it on Visa and First Data?

00:21:50.593 --> 00:21:52.510
GARY GENSLER: We were
in essence the merchant.

00:21:52.510 --> 00:21:54.740
And yes, we had to pay.

00:21:54.740 --> 00:21:57.700
The campaign-- and this happens
in every losing campaign.

00:21:57.700 --> 00:21:59.200
It didn't have
anything to do with--

00:21:59.200 --> 00:22:01.242
AUDIENCE: What if you've
already spent the money?

00:22:01.242 --> 00:22:02.570
GARY GENSLER: That's a problem.

00:22:02.570 --> 00:22:05.210
That's a real problem.

00:22:05.210 --> 00:22:09.990
And what the payment processing
companies-- in that case--

00:22:09.990 --> 00:22:11.720
it's a matter of public record.

00:22:11.720 --> 00:22:15.230
We used a company called
Stripe rather than First Data

00:22:15.230 --> 00:22:16.610
and so forth.

00:22:16.610 --> 00:22:19.570
I mean, the Stripes
of this world

00:22:19.570 --> 00:22:22.950
are taking some
counterparty risk.

00:22:22.950 --> 00:22:25.100
Now, most merchants
are not shutting down.

00:22:25.100 --> 00:22:28.150
We were shutting down.

00:22:28.150 --> 00:22:29.710
But yeah.

00:22:29.710 --> 00:22:34.220
So effectively it's
on the merchant.

00:22:34.220 --> 00:22:36.720
Cost of trust.

00:22:36.720 --> 00:22:40.020
In blockchain, there
is a cost of trust.

00:22:40.020 --> 00:22:42.150
But it's trusting the code--

00:22:42.150 --> 00:22:43.200
the computer code.

00:22:43.200 --> 00:22:47.250
You're trusting the Bitcoin
core developer, so to speak,

00:22:47.250 --> 00:22:50.080
and the consensus protocol.

00:22:50.080 --> 00:22:52.240
So when some people
say it's trustless,

00:22:52.240 --> 00:22:53.620
it's not truly trustless.

00:22:53.620 --> 00:22:55.120
You still have to
trust the code.

00:22:55.120 --> 00:22:58.600
You have to trust the consensus
protocol versus the trust

00:22:58.600 --> 00:22:59.930
in the central intermediary.

00:22:59.930 --> 00:23:02.070
So it's sort of trade-off of--

00:23:02.070 --> 00:23:02.740
yes, Aline.

00:23:02.740 --> 00:23:04.990
AUDIENCE: You're also trusting
the network in Bitcoin.

00:23:04.990 --> 00:23:06.723
Just a reminder.

00:23:06.723 --> 00:23:08.140
GARY GENSLER: Yes,
you're trusting

00:23:08.140 --> 00:23:09.560
the network in Bitcoin.

00:23:09.560 --> 00:23:10.820
It's a very good point.

00:23:10.820 --> 00:23:13.870
I think by and large we all
trust the network even when

00:23:13.870 --> 00:23:16.160
we're dealing with
Citibank as well.

00:23:16.160 --> 00:23:20.680
But you're right that right
in the center of a blockchain

00:23:20.680 --> 00:23:23.260
solution, you're trusting
the network for all

00:23:23.260 --> 00:23:25.360
its communications.

00:23:25.360 --> 00:23:27.880
But even at a
central intermediary,

00:23:27.880 --> 00:23:30.153
there's some trust in a network.

00:23:30.153 --> 00:23:31.820
AUDIENCE: Yeah, but
not for correctness.

00:23:31.820 --> 00:23:33.610
So in Bitcoin, you
can double spend

00:23:33.610 --> 00:23:35.530
if the network never messes up.

00:23:35.530 --> 00:23:39.250
But in a permissioned algorithm,
you cannot double spend--

00:23:39.250 --> 00:23:41.180
GARY GENSLER: There's
different issues.

00:23:41.180 --> 00:23:42.440
I agree with that.

00:23:42.440 --> 00:23:44.095
You had a question?

00:23:44.095 --> 00:23:45.970
AUDIENCE: I would go
one step further and say

00:23:45.970 --> 00:23:48.490
you also trust the ISP, right?

00:23:48.490 --> 00:23:50.770
Not just Citibank, but
you're trusting intermediary

00:23:50.770 --> 00:23:52.420
that gets you to
Citibank's website.

00:23:52.420 --> 00:23:52.720
But then I--

00:23:52.720 --> 00:23:53.803
GARY GENSLER: That's true.

00:23:53.803 --> 00:23:56.680
AUDIENCE: --can put a fake
website in between there.

00:23:56.680 --> 00:23:59.440
So there's layers of
trust all throughout this.

00:23:59.440 --> 00:24:00.900
GARY GENSLER: That's right.

00:24:00.900 --> 00:24:02.540
And I drive a car--

00:24:02.540 --> 00:24:03.680
not when I'm in Boston.

00:24:03.680 --> 00:24:06.080
When I drive a car, I'm
trusting the carburetor as well.

00:24:06.080 --> 00:24:08.390
And I don't really know
how a carburetor works.

00:24:11.360 --> 00:24:13.140
So there's all sorts
of layers of trust.

00:24:13.140 --> 00:24:16.040
But I would say that the central
trade-off with blockchain

00:24:16.040 --> 00:24:17.510
is you're moving
away from trusting

00:24:17.510 --> 00:24:19.520
the central intermediary.

00:24:19.520 --> 00:24:23.950
And you're trusting
code and consensus.

00:24:23.950 --> 00:24:26.410
And then economic rents,
and we've talked about this.

00:24:26.410 --> 00:24:29.890
I mean, it is not the
reason why payment systems

00:24:29.890 --> 00:24:32.530
cost a half a percent
to a percent of GDP

00:24:32.530 --> 00:24:33.640
around the globe.

00:24:33.640 --> 00:24:35.960
But some of that
is economic rents.

00:24:35.960 --> 00:24:37.810
And the financial
sector in the US

00:24:37.810 --> 00:24:40.510
is a trillion and a half
dollars or 7 and 1/2 percent

00:24:40.510 --> 00:24:41.810
of our economy.

00:24:41.810 --> 00:24:45.080
There's a fair degree of
economic rents in there.

00:24:45.080 --> 00:24:48.700
So these are kind of
the six or seven things

00:24:48.700 --> 00:24:52.790
