01:09:02.180 --> 01:09:06.290
It's sort of a newer modern-day
version of exchange traded

01:09:06.290 --> 01:09:12.800
funds, or it's a modern-day
version of warehouse receipts.

01:09:12.800 --> 01:09:16.640
Paper money started
exactly this way.

01:09:16.640 --> 01:09:22.460
Paper money was like, please,
will you store my grain

01:09:22.460 --> 01:09:24.840
and give me a warehouse receipt.

01:09:24.840 --> 01:09:25.939
And then it was gold.

01:09:25.939 --> 01:09:27.800
And I'll take a
warehouse receipt.

01:09:27.800 --> 01:09:31.840
And it was easier to exchange
the paper warehouse receipt

01:09:31.840 --> 01:09:34.080
than the gold or the
wheat and so forth.

01:09:34.080 --> 01:09:36.560
So I have to say, from an
economic point of view,

01:09:36.560 --> 01:09:37.620
there's a long history.

01:09:37.620 --> 01:09:40.160
The answer has to be yes.

01:09:40.160 --> 01:09:45.710
